      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tanuj Solanki" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tanuj Solanki" href="/user/show/4554994-tanuj-solanki">Tanuj Solanki</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140039597" href="/book/show/2310554.A_Universal_History_of_Infamy">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4554994-tanuj-solanki?shelf=argentina">argentina</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4554994-tanuj-solanki?shelf=spanish">spanish</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4554994-tanuj-solanki?shelf=south-america">south-america</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer410895318" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2710719226266889096">According to Borges, the stories here were meant for nothing graver than light entertainment. But today their chief purpose may well be to provide access to the writer&apos;s early dabbling. And yes, there are numerous signs of what was to come. There are mirrors here, and recursive systems, and hoaxes, and some mind-boggling endings too.<br/><br/>Though the stories are straightforward, re-reading provides greater pleasures, as with all Borges. The trivia is that each story was written as contribution to a wee</span>
  <span id="freeText2710719226266889096" style="display:none">According to Borges, the stories here were meant for nothing graver than light entertainment. But today their chief purpose may well be to provide access to the writer's early dabbling. And yes, there are numerous signs of what was to come. There are mirrors here, and recursive systems, and hoaxes, and some mind-boggling endings too.<br /><br />Though the stories are straightforward, re-reading provides greater pleasures, as with all Borges. The trivia is that each story was written as contribution to a weekly column in an Argentine newspaper - just to fill the space. This may amaze today's aspiring writers, a crowd of which we now face considerable proliferation. Such fecundity, such class, and such research is bound to appear downright incredible.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2710719226266889096" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


